flowRoot.flowPara: Response Signatures outperform Pathway Methods for Drug Associations

A. Comparison of pathway methods by association of a pathway with increased (green) or decreased (red) patient survival. Colors correspond to z-score (grey: FDR>20%, white: no pathway available). Method (vertical) and pathway (horizontal) labels as indicated. For our method, MAPK/EGFR provide the strongest negative contribution to survival. Trail/apoptosis is the only pathway mediating prolonged survival, but missing the significance threshold.

B. Volcano plot of cancers-specific associations between patient survival and inferred pathway score using our method, effect size on the x-axis, FDR-adjusted p-values on y. For these associations we can recover significant hits for apoptosis in multiple cancers and are the only method to do so.

D. Examples of Kaplan-Meier curves where our method is able to separate between groups of up-, downregulated pathways vs the rest. Hits shown are TNFa in KIRC, JAK-STAT in LGG, and Trail and CESC, where the stratification between top and bottom quartile is always at or greater than 25% after a year.
Response Signatures outperform Pathway Methods for Drug Associations

A. Volcano plot of cancers-specific associations between patient survival and inferred pathway score using our method (top) and GSEA using Reactome (middle) and Gene Ontology (bottom) sets. Effect size on the x-axis, FDR-adjusted p-values on y. Circle size corresponds to numre of data points, empty circles drop out of significance if conditioned.
B. As A, but using the SPIA and Pathifier methods.
C. Overview of pan-cancer associations for patient survival.
D. Examples of Kaplan-Meier curves where our method is able to separete between groups (p-values reported for continuous case).
